T1  - Do Hot Hands Exist among Hedge Fund Managers? An Empirical Evaluation
AU  - JAGANNATHAN, RAVI
AU  - MALAKHOV, ALEXEY
AU  - NOVIKOV, DMITRY
Y1  - 2010/02/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2009.01528.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 217
EP  - 255
VL  - 65
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2009.01528.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT In measuring performance persistence, we use hedge fund style benchmarks. This allows us to identify managers with valuable skills, and also to control for option-like features inherent in returns from hedge fund strategies. We take into account the possibility that reported asset values may be based on stale prices. We develop a statistical model that relates a hedge fund's performance to its decision to liquidate or close in order to infer the performance of a hedge fund that left the database. Although we find significant performance persistence among superior funds, we find little evidence of persistence among inferior funds.
ER  - 

